{
  "doc_id": "11947",
  "text": "Assessment of interaction is often performed by simply introducing product terms into logistic risk models. This practice has been criticized with arguments that the product term expresses interaction in a statistical meaning and not in a biological sense [CITATION_1] . Rothman's model of synergism used in the present study is based on the theory of two causes being component causes in the same sufficient cause [CITATION_2] . The criterion for interaction is departure from additivity and the reference group for the comparisons is the group unexposed to either factor. Rothman's model of synergism is based on additive models and was recommended in a review on how to evaluate interaction by Hallqvist et al. [CITATION_3] . This model has the advantages in that information from different types of studies can be employed, it has a theoretical background, and there is methodology to obtain confidence intervals from multiple regression software [CITATION_4] . There are also other methods of assessing measures of interaction as departure from additivity such as the attributable proportion (AP) and the relative excess risk due to interaction (RERI) [CITATION_5] . In the present study, early exposure to secondhand tobacco smoke and having allergic parents seemed to have a synergistic effect on the development of an allergy and allergic symptoms, enhancing the independent effects of heredity and secondhand tobacco smoke. Similar results were found in a study by Jaakkola et al. using a similar methodology of measuring interaction concluding that genetic heritage is a factor affected by secondhand smoke conditions and the odds of having asthma was more than twofold in children with an atopic heredity and early presence of secondhand tobacco smoke [CITATION_6] . Similar results were also found in a prospective multicenter birth cohort study by Keil et al. showing an increased risk of allergic sensitization and the development of asthma symptoms if the mother was smoking and if having allergic parents, while there was no increased risk if only having a smoking mother but no heredity [CITATION_7] . Furthermore, several experimental genetic studies confirm that genetic factors and secondhand factors act together and might modulate the development of allergy and asthma [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] .",
